Base quantities are physical quantities that are the most fundamental and they are independent of each other. Length Mass Time Amount of substance Temperature Current *Luminous intensity
Newton N kg m sˉ² Pascal Pa kg mˉ¹ sˉ² Joule J kg m² sˉ² Watt W kg m² sˉ³ Hertz Hz sˉ¹ Coulomb C A s Volt V kg m² sˉ³ Aˉ¹ Ohm Ω kg m² sˉ³ Aˉ²
An equation is homogeneous if every term on both sides of the equation have the same SI base units. A physically correct equation must be homogeneous!
When making an estimate, it is only reasonable to give the figure to 1 significant figure since an estimate is not very precise.
A scientifically measurable physical quantity has a numerical magnitude and a unit
Error is the difference between the measured value and the ‘true value’. Sources of errors can come from man, machine, material, experimental technique or environment.

Random error is an error which causes measurements to be sometimes larger than the true value and sometimes smaller than the true value. Reduce by -repeating the measurements to obtain an average value. -plot a graph to obtain best fit line.

Systematic error is an error which causes measurements to be either, always larger than the true value, or always smaller than the true value. -Zero error or -Incorrectly calibrated instrument -Using the wrong constant -wrong expt method
Precision refers to the degree of agreement (scatter, spread) of repeated measurements of the same quantity.
Accuracy refers to the degree of agreement between the result of measurement(s) and the true value of the quantity.
If Y = nA + mB, ( n & m are constants), → ΔY = |n|ΔA + |m|ΔB
If Y = aXⁿZᵐ (a, n & m are constants) → ΔY/Y = n ΔX/X + m ΔZ/Z
A scalar quantity has a magnitude only. It does not have a direction. It is completely described by a numerical value and a unit.
A vector quantity has both magnitude and direction.
